[0.000, "o", "\u001b[32m╭─\u001b[0m\u001b[32m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\u001b[32m \u001b[0m\u001b[1;32mAssistant\u001b[0m\u001b[32m \u001b[0m\u001b[32m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\u001b[32m─╮\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                     \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  To check for system updates on openSUSE, you can follow these steps:                                                               \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                     \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m 1 \u001b[0mLog in to your server using SSH or a terminal emulator such as PuTTY (i"]
[0.000, "o", "f you're not already familiar with it). 2. Open the      \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0mcommand line and navigate to your /etc/yast directory by typing \"cd /etc\" followed by enter. This will take you into YAST       \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0mconfiguration files, which are used for managing system updates in openSUSE. 3. Look at the file named \"updates\", located       \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0munder \"/usr/share/YaSt\". You can find this file using a text editor like vi or nano (if you're not familiar with it). This is   \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0mwhere YAST stores information about available and installed system updates, including their status, version number,             \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0minstallation location, etc. 4. If there are any new system update packages that need to be applied, the file will have a \"new\"  \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0mor \"updated\" line in its contents (depending on whether it's an install package or upgr"]
[0.000, "o", "ade). This indicates which files and     \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0mdirectories should be re-downloaded/reinstalled for you to get up-to-date. 5. If there are no new system update packages, the   \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0mfile will have a blank space where \"new\" or \"updated\" lines would go (depending on whether it's an install package or           \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0mupgrade). This indicates that everything is already installed and ready to use on your server. Note: OpenSUSE uses its own      \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m  \u001b[36m   \u001b[0mYAST tool for managing system updates, which you can find in the \"/usr/share/YaSt\" directory by typing \"ls /usr/share/YaSt\".    \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m│\u001b[0m                                                                                                                                     \u001b[32m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[32m╰───────────────────────────────────────────"]
[0.000, "o", "──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╯\u001b[0m\r\n"]
[0.001, "o", "\u001b[2m╭─\u001b[0m\u001b[2m─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\u001b[2m \u001b[0m\u001b[2mSources\u001b[0m\u001b[2m \u001b[0m\u001b[2m─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\u001b[0m\u001b[2m─╮\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[2m│\u001b[0m \u001b[2m  • Installation Quick Start | Start-Up | openSUSE Leap 15.6 (42%)\u001b[0m                                                                  \u001b[2m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[2m│\u001b[0m \u001b[2;34m    https://doc.opensuse.org/documentation/leap/startup/html/book-startup/art-opensuse-installquick.html\u001b[0m                            \u001b[2m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[2m│\u001b[0m \u001b[2m  • Installation steps | Start-Up | openSUSE Leap 15.6 (42%)\u001b[0m                                                                        \u001b[2m│\u001b[0m\r\n\u001b[2m│\u001b[0m \u001b[2;34m    https://doc.opensuse.org/documentation/leap/startup/ht"]
